\begin_layout Subsection
Modular Variables and Displacement Operators | prior art
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The observables admissible in the CHSH inequality must 
\begin_inset Formula $\in[-1,1]$
\end_inset

.
 If we consider the 
\emph on
real
\emph default
 
\emph on
variable
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in(-\infty,\infty)$
\end_inset

, then one way of obtaining a bound variable is to use 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{mod}\equiv p\mod h/L$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $h/L$
\end_inset

 has been introduced for dimensional reasons.
 This forces 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{mod}\in[0,h/L)$
\end_inset

.
 If I further consider, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(p_{mod}L/\hbar)$
\end_inset

, then I get precisely the bound needed for the CHSH inequality.
 I chose the factor so that for 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{mod}=h/L$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos$
\end_inset

function also completes a period.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(p_{mod}L/\hbar)=\cos(pL/\hbar)=\frac{e^{ipL/\hbar}+e^{-ipL/\hbar}}{\sqrt{2}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, recall that in quantum mechanics, the momentum that's quantized, is
 one that generates infinitesimal translations.
 Formally, this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1-i\hat{p}\delta L/\hbar\right)\left|x\right\rangle =\left|x+\delta L\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 If I want a finite translation, I can do the following procedure: 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{N\to\infty}\left(1-i\frac{\hat{p}}{\hbar}\frac{L}{N}\right)^{N}\left|x\right\rangle =e^{-i\hat{p}L/\hbar}\left|x\right\rangle =\left|x+L\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 This operator is aptly called the displacement operator.
 We must add that 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\hat{p}a}e^{i\hat{x}b}=e^{i\hbar ab}e^{i\hat{x}b}e^{i\hat{p}a}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus for appropriate choices of 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

, the displacement operators can be made to commute or anti-commute.
 In the former case, it means one can simultaneously measure modular position
 and momentum (which is striking) and in the latter case, one can define
 pauli matrix like commutation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea was that the obvious generalization for obtaining an appropriate
 operator for the CHSH inequality is 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(\hat{p}L/\hbar)=\frac{e^{i\hat{p}L/\hbar}+e^{i\hat{p}L/\hbar}}{\sqrt{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 The action of the operator will guide us in creating the appropriate states
 in the next sub section.
\end_layout

