\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
W_{1}(q',p') & = & \frac{1}{2\pi\hbar}\int dqe^{ip'q/\hbar}\left\langle q'-\frac{q}{2}\right|e^{-iZ(\hat{x}_{mod2L})\phi/2}\\
 &  & e^{i\hat{p}\frac{L}{\hbar}}e^{iZ(\hat{x}_{mod2L})\phi/2}\left|q'+\frac{q}{2}\right\rangle \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2\pi\hbar}e^{-iZ_{1}(q')\phi/2}e^{ip'\frac{L}{\hbar}}e^{iZ_{2}(q')\phi/2}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{2\pi\hbar}e^{ip'L/\hbar}e^{iZ_{2}(q')\phi}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{1/2}(q')=Z[(q'\mp\frac{L}{2})\mod2L]$
\end_inset

 and we used the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(x')=-Z(x'+L)$
\end_inset

 (omitting the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mod2L$
\end_inset

).
 Similarly one can evaluate 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{2}$
\end_inset

 and obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W=\left(W_{1}+W_{2}\right)/2=\frac{1}{2\pi\hbar}\cos(p'L/\hbar)e^{\pm i\phi}
\]

\end_inset

 which corresponds to the observable (we used that 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{2}=\pm1$
\end_inset

).
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|W\right|\le\left(2\pi\hbar\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Source of Violation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Bell test done with spins, the source of violation hinges on the
 non-commutativity of the Pauli matrices.
 It is known that 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{2}=4\mathbb{I}+[a_{1},a_{2}]\otimes[b_{1},b_{2}]$
\end_inset

, when 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i},b_{i}\in\{-1,1\}$
\end_inset

.
 To obtain a violation in general (where the first term maybe less than
 
\begin_inset Formula $4\mathbb{I}$
\end_inset

), it is therefore necessary that the commutations don't vanish.
 This is indeed true in our case.
 Explicitly, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $[\hat{U}^{\dagger}\hat{X}\hat{U},\hat{U}'^{\dagger}\hat{X}\hat{U}']\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 To arrive at the desired expression we first evaluate some simpler commutation
 and anti-commutation relations explicitly.
 Let's start with 
\begin_inset Formula $[\hat{Z},e^{i\hat{p}L/\hbar}]=\hat{Z}e^{i\hat{p}L/\hbar}-e^{i\hat{p}L/\hbar}\hat{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 To evaluate it, we multiply the second term with 
\begin_inset Formula $\int dx\left|x\right\rangle \left\langle x\right|$
\end_inset

 and obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $Ze^{i\hat{p}L/\hbar}+Ze^{i\hat{p}L/\hbar}$
\end_inset

 where we've used 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(\hat{x}_{mod2L})=-Z(\left(\hat{x}\pm L\right)_{mod2L})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\hat{p}L/\hbar}\left|x\right\rangle =\left|x-L\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[\hat{Z},\hat{X}]=2\hat{Z}\hat{X}=-2i\hat{Y}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}=i\hat{Z}\hat{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 was introduced to ensure 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}^{\dagger}=\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\dagger}=X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Z}^{\dagger}=\hat{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\hat{Z},\hat{X}\}=0$
\end_inset

.
 From the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and the anti-commutation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\hat{Y},\hat{X}\}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\hat{Y},\hat{Z}\}=0$
\end_inset

 also follow trivially.
 While we're at it, we may state that while 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Z}^{2}=1$
\end_inset

, it is not a sum of a 2 state projector and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}^{2}\neq1$
\end_inset

 in general.
 This manifests in the other commutation relations 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
[\hat{X},\hat{Y}] & = & -2i\hat{Z}\hat{X}^{2}=-2i\hat{X}^{2}\hat{Z}\\{}
[\hat{Y},\hat{Z}] & = & -2i\hat{X}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Further, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-i\hat{Z}\phi/2}Xe^{i\hat{Z}\phi/2}=Xe^{i\hat{Z}\phi}$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\hat{Z}\phi}=\cos\phi+i\hat{Z}\sin\phi$
\end_inset

.
 With all these, it is easy to show that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
[U^{\dagger}(\frac{\phi}{2})XU(\frac{\phi}{2}),U^{\dagger}(\frac{\phi'}{2})XU(\frac{\phi'}{2})] & =\\
\left(\cos\phi\sin\phi'-\sin\phi\cos\phi'\right)\hat{Z}\hat{X}^{2} & \neq & 0
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

as was necessary.
 Ofcourse this is not sufficient, however we have shown explicitly the violation.
 This evaluation was meant to illuminate that the source of violation essentiall
y hinges on the non-commutativity of 
\begin_inset Formula $[\hat{x}_{mod2L},\hat{p}_{modL}]\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 It is apparent that the complete pauli algebra is unnecessary for showing
 a violation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Advantage of asymmetry in 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Z}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Considering the operator (non-hermitian for simplicity) 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}=e^{i\hat{p}L/\hbar}$
\end_inset

, defining 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Z}=e^{i\hat{x}2\pi/2L}$
\end_inset

 is more natural.
 They also follow the desired anti-commutation 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\hat{X},\hat{Z}\}=0$
\end_inset

 and we could define 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}=\hat{iZ}\hat{X}$
\end_inset

 to get a more natural generalization.
 The question is why did we choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Z}=Z(\hat{x}_{mod2L})$
\end_inset

.
 The cause of this asymmetry hinges on the preferential treatment of position
 space.
 We could have constructed states of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0'\right\rangle =\sum_{n}\left|x+nd\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and used the natural definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Z}$
\end_inset

 to obtain the violation.
 The issue is that this forces me to choose a countable superposition of
 position eigenkets as my state.
 Such a state is strictly not even in the Hilbert space.
 In the scheme proposed, this issue is resolved by 
\begin_inset Formula $Z(\hat{x}_{mod2L})$
\end_inset

 which causes a larger set of physically realizable states become admissible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus while our construction is motivated by the spin formalism, it is not
 just a relabelling of states and operators achieved by a severe restriction
 of the Hilbert space.
 
\end_layout

