\begin_layout Subsection
Creation of the entangled state
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The desired entangled state is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Psi\right\rangle \equiv\frac{\left|+-\right\rangle -\left|-+\right\rangle }{\sqrt{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 We start with noting the triviality of constructing a 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|+'\right\rangle =\frac{1}{\sqrt{2N}}\sum_{n\in I_{2N}}\left|\varphi_{n}\right\rangle 
\]

\end_inset

 state.
 One simply needs a source and a grating, viz.
 a screen with 
\begin_inset Formula $2N$
\end_inset

 slits of width 
\begin_inset Formula $a\ll L$
\end_inset

, separated by a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 (centre to centre).
 The 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|-'\right\rangle =\frac{1}{\sqrt{2N}}\sum_{n\in I_{2N}}\left(-1\right)^{n+1}\left|\varphi_{n}\right\rangle 
\]

\end_inset

 state can be similarly constructed by using glass slabs at alternate slits,
 such that the phase introduced is 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\pi\,\implies\, e^{i\phi}=-1$
\end_inset

.
 In figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:scheme"

\end_inset

, if you consider only one particle, and disregard everything after the
 grating, then the setup is expected to produce a 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|+\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 state, just after the grating.
 To produce the desired entangled state, we start with two entangled photons,
 such that their polarization state can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|\chi\right\rangle =\frac{\left|HV\right\rangle -\left|VH\right\rangle }{\sqrt{2}}
\]

\end_inset

Their spatial description (along 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-axis) is initially assumed to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\zeta\right\rangle =\left|\gamma\right\rangle \otimes\left|\gamma\right\rangle =\left|\gamma\gamma\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 The state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\gamma\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 maybe considered to be a guassian with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\gg2NL$
\end_inset

 so that after the grating, the spatial state can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\zeta_{\text{grating}}\right\rangle =\left|+'+'\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 Now comes the interesting part.
 To produce a 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|-'\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 state, we already know we needed alternate glass slabs.
 If we had glass slabs, whose refractive index (given some orientation)
 was say 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{H}=1$
\end_inset

 for a horizontally polarized beam and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{V}=\eta\neq0$
\end_inset

 for vertical polarization, then we could harness the entangled polarization
 state to create the required spatially entangled state.
 Birefringent crystals have such polarization dependent refractive indices.
 Assume that alternating birefringent crystals have been placed after both
 the gratings as shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:scheme"

\end_inset

 (in the diagram, they're not alternating though).
 These have width such that the resultant phase it introduces is 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

.
 The combined initial state is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|\chi\right\rangle \left|\zeta\right\rangle =\frac{\left|HV\right\rangle -\left|VH\right\rangle }{\sqrt{2}}\left|\gamma\gamma\right\rangle 
\]

\end_inset

After the grating, the state is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|\chi\right\rangle \left|\zeta_{\text{grating}}\right\rangle =\frac{\left|HV\right\rangle -\left|VH\right\rangle }{\sqrt{2}}\left|+'+'\right\rangle 
\]

\end_inset

And finally after the crystals, the combined state becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|\chi\right\rangle \left|\zeta_{\text{birefringent}}\right\rangle =\frac{\left|HV\right\rangle \left|+'-'\right\rangle -\left|VH\right\rangle \left|-'+'\right\rangle }{\sqrt{2}}
\]

\end_inset

At this stage, if I were to trace out the polarization state, I'd end up
 with a mixed state.
 That is useless for our test.
 Ignoring the glass slabs at the moment in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:scheme"

\end_inset

, we observe the action of the polarisers on the state.
 After the 
\begin_inset Formula $45^{0}$
\end_inset

 polariser, the state becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left|\chi_{\text{45}}\right\rangle \left|\zeta_{\text{birefringent}}\right\rangle  & \propto & \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\bigg(\frac{\left|H\right\rangle +\left|V\right\rangle }{\sqrt{2}}\frac{\left|H\right\rangle +\left|V\right\rangle }{\sqrt{2}}\left|+'-'\right\rangle \\
 &  & -\frac{\left|H\right\rangle +\left|V\right\rangle }{\sqrt{2}}\frac{\left|H\right\rangle +\left|V\right\rangle }{\sqrt{2}}\left|-'+'\right\rangle \bigg)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Rewriting 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\left|H\right\rangle +\left|V\right\rangle \right)/\sqrt{2}=\left|H'\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, I get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|\chi_{\text{45}}\right\rangle \left|\zeta_{\text{birefringent}}\right\rangle \propto\left|H'H'\right\rangle \left(\frac{\left|+'-'\right\rangle -\left|-'+'\right\rangle }{\sqrt{2}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Now if I trace out the polarization state, I am left with the target entangled
 state.
 As a remark, it maybe be stated that although to arrive at this result
 we assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{H}=1$
\end_inset

, which is unreasonable physically, we can compensate for 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{H}\neq0$
\end_inset

 by putting appropriate glass slabs at the alternate empty slits, to produce
 zero relative phase when the polarization is horizontal.
\end_layout

