\begin_layout Subsection
Measurement Settings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our scheme, Alice and Bob can choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\in\{\phi_{1},\phi_{2}\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in\{\theta_{1},\theta_{2}\}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 To implement this, we note that the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{U}(\theta)$
\end_inset

 is to introduce a phase difference between the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0'\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|1'\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 states.
 By construction, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0'\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|1'\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 are spatially disjoint; thus the operation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{U}(\theta)$
\end_inset

 can be implemented by simply placing alternating glass slabs at the slits,
 with widths such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0'\right\rangle \to e^{i\theta/2}\left|0'\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|1'\right\rangle \to e^{-i\theta/2}\left|1'\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 The same operation maybe done for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{U}(\phi)$
\end_inset

 for the second particle.
 In the overall scheme, as shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:scheme"

\end_inset

, this is done by the glass slabs right after the birefringent crystals.
 The state after application of the unitaries is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Psi_{f}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is used to index which of the four possible measurement settings was used.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Measurement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The scheme requires us to evaluate the expectation value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}\otimes\hat{X}$
\end_inset

 (after the measurement settings have been applied by the appropriate unitaries).
 If from the experiment, we can obtain the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\left\langle p{}_{A},p{}_{B}|\Psi_{f}\right\rangle \right|^{2}$
\end_inset

, then evaluating 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \hat{X}\otimes\hat{X}\right\rangle =\left\langle \cos(\hat{p}L/\hbar)\otimes\cos(\hat{p}L/\hbar)\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 simply amounts to 
\begin_inset Formula $\int dp{}_{A}dp{}_{B}\cos(p{}_{A}L/\hbar)\cos(p{}_{B}L/\hbar)\left|\left\langle p{}_{A},p{}_{B}|\Psi_{f}\right\rangle \right|^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore it is sufficient to explain how to obtain the joint momentum probabili
ty distribution from the experiment, for a given measurement setting.
 We start with stating the result that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|\left\langle x{}_{A},x{}_{B}|\Psi{}_{f\,\text{screen}}\right\rangle \right|^{2}\propto\left|\left\langle p{}_{A}=\frac{p_{z}x{}_{A}}{D},p{}_{B}=\frac{p_{z}x{}_{B}}{D}|\Psi_{f}\right\rangle \right|^{2}
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Psi{}_{f\,\text{screen}}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is the state of the system at the screen, 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is the distance between the gratings and the screens and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{z}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 component of momentum of the particle.
 For a photon, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{z}=h/\lambda$
\end_inset

 while for an electron, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{z}=m_{e}D/T$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is the time taken to arrive at the screen from the grating.
 The idea is simply that the momentum distribution at the grating can be
 recovered by observing the spatial distribution at a screen, sufficiently
 far away.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In an experiment then, there are two possibilities.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

(a) Given 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, Alice and Bob both note the position at which they obtain their particle.
 After repeating the experiment sufficiently many times, they share their
 list to create a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\left(x{}_{A}^{(i)},x_{B}^{(i)}\right)\}$
\end_inset

.
 From this sequence, they create a 2D histogram, by simply counting how
 many time they got 
\begin_inset Formula $(x'_{A},x'_{B})$
\end_inset

 to lie inside a given cell.
 The normalized result is essentially 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\left\langle x{}_{A},x{}_{B}|\Psi{}_{f\,\text{screen}}\right\rangle \right|^{2}$
\end_inset

 from which 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle X\otimes X\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 can be computed as discussed.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is changed to evaluate all the 4 terms to finally obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle C\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 experimentally.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

(b) The other simpler, equivalent and direct possibility is that Alice and
 Bob both obtain the position, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x_{A}^{(i)},x_{B}^{(i)}\}$
\end_inset

 for the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th repetition and evaluate 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(p_{A}^{(i)}L/\hbar)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(p_{B}^{(i)}L/\hbar)$
\end_inset

.
 After sufficient iterations, they exchange their observations to simply
 evaluate the average, viz.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\sum_{i}\cos(p_{A}^{(i)}L/\hbar)\cos(p_{B}^{(i)}L/\hbar)}{\sum_{i}}=\left\langle C\right\rangle 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

